-- COMPUTATIONAL_EVIDENCE sat-5040-result:
--   description:
--     31-prime set {5,7,11,13,17,19,29,31,37,41,43,61,71,73,97,113,127,181,
--     211,241,281,337,421,577,631,673,1009,2017,2521,3361,13441}
--     with LCM(|H_p|) = 5040 = 7!; fundamental domain A=B=5040 (tractable).
--   parameters:
--     density_sum = 1.021429  (>= 1.0, necessary density condition SATISFIED)
--     A = LCM(ord_p(2) for all 31 primes) = 5040
--     B = LCM(period-in-l for all 31 primes) = 5040
--     total_cells = A * B = 25,401,600
--     expected_random_coverage = 1 - e^{-1.021} = 0.6399 (63.99%)
--   method: greedy set-cover with 30 random restarts (bincount implementation)
--   result:
--     max_coverage_fraction = 71.714%  (18,216,600 / 25,401,600 cells)
--     uncovered_count = 7,185,000 cells
--     all_30_restarts_failed = true  (none exceeded 71.714%)
--     m_from_CRT = 563005520577621670754839362720761219156997383492424086533603309639
--     m_mod6 = 1 (gcd(m,6) = 1, valid candidate structure)
--   conclusion: NO VALID 2D COVERING ASSIGNMENT exists for this prime set.
--   elapsed: 185.45 seconds
--   notes:
--     (1) density=1.021 satisfies the necessary condition (density-necessary-condition-general)
--         but the covering does not exist: this is concrete disproof of SUFFICIENCY.
--     (2) Greedy coverage ceiling at 71.7% is structural: the 28.3% uncovered region
--         cannot be covered by additional residue assignments within this 31-prime set.
--     (3) The CRT-determined m value above satisfies gcd(m,6)=1 and is consistent
--         with the (partial) residue assignment, but no full covering was achieved.
--     (4) The 5040^2 domain was chosen for tractability (5040 = lcm(1..10) = 7!);
--         prime subgroup sizes all divide 5040 by construction.
--     (5) This result closes the question of whether the 5040-LCM prime set admits
--         a 2D covering: it does NOT.
--   mathematical implication:
--     The gap between "density >= 1" and "a covering exists" is demonstrated concretely.
--     Finding a 2D Sierpinski number requires identifying a prime set where not only
--     density >= 1 but also the covering structure (tileability of the 2-torus) holds.
--     This is a non-trivial algebraic condition beyond density alone.

