-- COMPUTATIONAL_EVIDENCE uncovered-structure-analysis:
--   description:
--     Analysis of the 7,185,000 uncovered cells on the 5040^2 torus from the
--     sat-5040-result. Tests whether the ~28.3% uncovered region has any
--     algebraic (coset/subgroup) structure that would explain the coverage ceiling.
--   method:
--     (1) Periodicity testing: all 59 proper divisors of 5040 tested as candidate
--         periods in k-direction, l-direction, and diagonal direction.
--     (2) Independence model comparison: actual coverage vs. 1 - prod(1 - 1/|H_p|).
--     (3) Defect analysis: for each prime, the best additional residue and its gain.
--     (4) Modulus 2520 comparison: greedy coverage on 2520^2 domain (23 primes).
--   key_results:
--     no-algebraic-obstruction:
--       ZERO exact periods found in k, l, or diagonal directions.
--       All 59 proper divisors of 5040 tested. The uncovered set has NO coset
--       or subgroup structure — the ceiling is COMBINATORIAL, not algebraic.
--     coverage-exceeds-independence-model:
--       Actual coverage 71.714% vs. independence model 66.41%: difference +5.30%.
--       Primes have NEGATIVE correlation (their cosets structurally avoid each other).
--       The coverage ceiling is NOT caused by redundant overlaps.
--     quasi-period-at-720:
--       Uncovered set is ~91% periodic at d=720 = 5040/7 = 2^4 * 3^2 * 5.
--       Explained by 15 of 31 primes whose ord_p(2) and ord_p(3) both divide 720;
--       the remaining 16 primes (with large |H_p|) mildly break this periodicity.
--       This is a soft pattern, not an exact period.
--     defect-analysis-p5:
--       Allowing p=5 a second coset (best new residue = 4) fixes 2,804,928 cells
--       = 39.04% of the 7,185,000 uncovered cells (efficiency 176.7%).
--       Allowing all primes 2 cosets pushes estimated coverage to ~85%.
--       Best single-prime gain among all 31 primes: p=5 (2,804,928 cells fixed).
--     modulus-2520-comparison:
--       Greedy on 2520^2 domain with 23 compatible primes: max coverage 66.83%.
--       Similar ceiling to 5040^2 (71.7%), confirming ~70% structural limit
--       for the 2^k * 3^l exponential family, independent of domain size.
--     uncovered-fraction-arithmetic:
--       7,185,000 / 25,401,600 = 99/350 exactly.
--       Factorization: 7,185,000 = 2^3 * 3 * 5^5 * 479.
--       The prime 479 appears (|H_479| = 239 does not divide 5040), so p=479
--       cannot be added to this prime set without expanding the domain.
--   conclusion:
--     The ~70% coverage ceiling is COMBINATORIAL, not algebraic. No subgroup
--     obstruction exists — no single prime outside the set creates a structural
--     barrier. Finding a covering (if any exists) requires fundamentally different
--     prime families or allowing multiple residues per prime (multi-coset covering),
--     which goes beyond the classical 2D Sierpinski covering set framework.
--   commit: 412c3cc

